As usual, you are wrong, dead wrong. Tablets are replacing computers, especially laptops. It&#39;s apparent to everyone. <br><BR><font size=1>20:45 10-24-2012</font><BR><BR>My lord, it&#39;s just an eye. The gods saw fit to grace me with a spare</TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Lt. Cabbage </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Lt. Cabbage '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">Agreed it will work better than alternatives for Office. However, that isn&#39;t such an essential requirement now.  I  can update Google Docs or a Google Drive-stored Excel file on the iPad (Word formatting goes screwy however).  It is true that the Surface should make sense for students. <br><BR><font size=1>18:10 10-24-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Jedi Genius '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">It&#39;s no more expensive than an iPad. People complain about a $100 keyboard cover, but forget that an iPad magnetic cover is $40... and it&#39;s just a cover. For the extra $60, you get productivity tools (Office) and a keyboard that doesn&#39;t take up half the screen to type on. <br />
<br />
The Surface is clearly more than a media consumption device. If that&#39;s what you want, the Kindle/Nook/Nexus 7 are by far the better purchases at $200-$250. If you were considering buying a low end laptop to do the standard chatting/email/browsing PLUS would like the ability to be productive with Office stuff (virtually every student or office worker), then Surface becomes a much better option (and certainly is more capable than the iPad). <br />
<br />
Microsoft is clearly trying to redefine the "between full out laptop and smartphone" space with something you can use to consume AND create with. It&#39;s a good direction to go in and definitely plays to their strengths (Office). <br><BR><font size=1>17:53 10-24-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Lt. Cabbage </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Lt. Cabbage '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont"><blockquote><i>will likely be something people purchase in addition to a laptop or desktop</i></blockquote><br />
See here I feel it has a problem.  It&#39;s more expensive than the market leading iPad, let alone some much cheaper Androids.  When it&#39;s being viewed as a purchase alongside a full computer, the jack-of-all-trades nature becomes a weakness, not a strength. <br><BR><font size=1>17:43 10-24-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Jedi Genius '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">By the way, Windows RT is immune to malware much like iOS is, since the only apps it can install are Microsoft approved.  <br><BR><font size=1>17:29 10-24-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Jedi Genius '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">So I finally have a keyboard to type on (rather than on my phone), so I can finally write something of substance on here:<br />
<br />
1) I never said the iPad would fail. I said it would never replace laptops, and that it would be a pure luxury item that people would buy in addition to a computer. Neal disputed this and felt like it would replace actual computers. Well, the iPad is a complete luxury item, and the vast majority are purchased to be used in addition to a computer. There is no "need" for an iPad, considering a smartphone and laptop does everything an iPad does already. I see nothing incorrect about anything I said. <br />
<br />
2) Never said Windows Phone would be a huge hit. I said it was good. I said Microsoft would never give up supporting it even if it took years to sell. Seriously, I dare you to find where I said it would be a huge success. Neal claimed it would be a huge flop. It has started slowly, but Rome wasn&#39;t built in a week. WP8 is a huge step forward, and with the same kernel as Windows 8 and Windows RT, porting programs from desktop to phone will be easy... and no developer is going to ignore Windows 8, given the massive install base Windows has. Every defense I made for Windows Phone was in its capabilities and how it&#39;s a long term play for Microsoft in response to Neal&#39;s doom and gloom comments based on what he read.<br />
<br />
3) Surface is another "long term play". You can&#39;t judge success based on reviews 2 days before launch, especially not when the success of a product relies just as much on software and developer support as it does on capable hardware. Well, the hardware is there, and the software will be there in the coming months. You can&#39;t go from 0 to 100k apps in a matter of a couple of weeks. If we come back to look at Surface in January, I&#39;ll bet the app store is more fully fleshed out with most, if not all, of the key apps available. Calling it a flop before it even launches is premature and foolish. The first Xbox was a "flop", but it was another long term play by Microsoft that they got right in the second iteration... and they got the key developers on board (i.e. Rockstar to make GTA for Xbox). Windows RT, and by extension Surface, will get there too. <br />
<br />
As for Surface RT as a laptop replacement - if your key functions on a laptop are chatting, email, browsing, media consumption, games, and Office, then Surface RT will work for you. It has a HDMI port to connect a larger monitor if needed. It has the "Type" cover, which has actual keys on it and is only 3mm thicker than the Touch cover. It has bluetooth so you can connect a full out regular keyboard to it. It has a real USB port to connect accessories to it (cameras, printers, etc). You can use your Xbox360 controller to play games on it. It has long battery life (tests show 9 1/2+ hours). <br />
<br />
The real limitations are lack of ability to run legacy software and no full on PC games (i.e. WoW and stuff). In order to run that stuff, you&#39;d need a Windows 8 tablet with an Atom processor (the one they use to put in Netbooks) or AMD/Intel Core processor. These tablets will have worse battery life, won&#39;t have "always on" connections to Wifi (because it drains the battery too quickly with these processors), and will be thicker and heavier. The non-Atom versions will most likely have internal fans for cooling. BUT they will still be the most portable, usable, capable touchscreen tablets in the market and will be able to utilize keyboard docks, a mouse, and external monitors. They will be true laptop replacements for people who need their computer to do everything.<br />
<br />
Windows RT can be used as a laptop replacement for very basic users, but will likely be something people purchase in addition to a laptop or desktop. But unless you&#39;re an early adopter of stuff (remember, even the iPad had seriously weak app support at first), you&#39;ll be best served to wait a couple of months to see what apps look like then and also to see what other PC makers come out with for hardware. Hell, you might even see prices start to drop some or catch a promotion or two for bundled stuff. <br />
<br />
Windows RT/Windows 8 is a long term play, a strategic change for Microsoft that makes the 4 screens all look similar and work together (PC, tablet, tv (through xbox360), phone). 3 of those 4 use the same kernel and will have a lot of apps working together. Smartglass ties Phone/Tablet/PC to your TV even closer. It will take time to develop into full potential, but Microsoft will succeed. It&#39;s not like businesses are lining up to switch to OSX, and it&#39;s not like they&#39;ll ever switch away from Office. <br><BR><font size=1>17:28 10-24-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>Lt. Cabbage </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Lt. Cabbage '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">Then of course you could just get your computer fixed, or reinstall Windows, and use it for virtually nothing but music management.  Do everything else on a tablet.<br />
<br />
For PCs, I also use Microsoft Security Essentials. <br><BR><font size=1>16:57 10-24-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Lt. Cabbage </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Lt. Cabbage '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">ITunes would be a problem.  I thought Zune runs in some fashion, but I don&#39;t know enough about Zune to say if it&#39;ll be limited.  I think I&#39;d rather keep a full computer for music management though.  You can get a perfectly good laptop for so cheap that even adding a tablet on top won&#39;t cost that much.  Cheap laptop + iPad is well below the cost of a MacBook Pro. <br><BR><font size=1>16:33 10-24-2012</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/heroclix/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Patrick M. S '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">all I use my PC for is:<br />
